Let's start by locating the missing `wallet.dat` file on your Windows 10 machine. Since Bitcoin Core uses a Berkeley DB file format, we can use a simple PowerShell script to scan likely folders for files that have the right internal fingerprint—without needing to install anything or expose any wallet contents.

Copy and paste the following into a **PowerShell** window (right-click the Start button → **Windows PowerShell**). This will search your Documents folder, the default Bitcoin Core data directory, and your external drive (`D:\Backup2021\`; adjust the letter if yours is different). It looks for any `.dat` file starting with eight zero bytes—a strong indicator of a Bitcoin Core wallet—and prints the full path:

```powershell
$paths = @(
    "$env:USERPROFILE\Documents",
    "$env:APPDATA\Bitcoin",
    "D:\Backup2021"
)

foreach ($searchPath in $paths) {
    if (Test-Path $searchPath) {
        Get-ChildItem -Path $searchPath -Recurse -Filter *.dat -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {
            $bytes = [System.IO.File]::ReadAllBytes($_.FullName)
            if ($bytes.Length -ge 8 -and ($bytes[0..7] | ForEach-Object { $_ -eq 0 }) -notcontains $false) {
                Write-Host "Candidate wallet: $($_.FullName)"
            }
        }
    } else {
        Write-Host "Note: Path not found or not accessible: $searchPath"
    }
}
```

After you run it, please share **only the full file paths** it outputs (e.g., `C:\Users\name\Documents\wallet.dat`). **Do not paste or share any file contents.**

If you know of other folders or drives where you might have stored a backup, you can add them to the `$paths` list before running. Also, the external drive letter might not be `D:`—adjust it to match yours.

Once we have a confirmed path, we’ll move on to setting up BTCRecover on your Windows machine, taking it offline, and then attempting to recover your password using a tokenlist built from your remembered pattern.

